This paper deals with the semantics of logic programming, specifically in the context of higher-order logic programming with negation. This makes it likely to belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) category. Additionally, the paper discusses non-monotonic fixed-point theory, which is a common topic in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) research. The paper also deals with the properties of logic programming, which is a topic in Programming Languages (cs.PL). The use of models and semantics suggests that the paper could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. Finally, the paper discusses a paradox related to the semantics of higher-order logic programming, which could make it relevant to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category.
